06217nam a22008895i 9780812296983DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122969837 a10.9783/97808122969832doi  a(DE-B1597)563113  a(OCoLC)1145430947  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a994.1/32231 aGonzález Zarandona, José Antonio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMurujuga :bRock Art, Heritage, and Landscape Iconoclasm /cJosé Antonio González Zarandona. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b66 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Murujuga -- tChapter 1. Situating Murujuga -- tChapter 2. Murujuga and Its Meanings -- tPart II. From the Colonial Gaze to the Academic Appreciation of Rock Art -- tChapter 3. The Colonial Gaze -- tChapter 4. Rude Aesthetics -- tChapter 5. The Colonization of the Landscape -- tPart III. Landscape and Heritage -- tChapter 6. The Destruction of Landscape in Murujuga -- tChapter 7. The Making of Heritage -- tPart IV. A Theory of Landscape Iconoclasm -- tChapter 8. Landscape Iconoclasm -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA fascinating case study of the archaeological site at Murujuga, AustraliaLocated in the Dampier Archipelago of Western Australia, Murujuga is the single largest archaeological site in the world. It contains an estimated one million petroglyphs, or rock art motifs, produced by the Indigenous Australians who have historically inhabited the archipelago. To date, there has been no comprehensive survey of the site's petroglyphs or those who created them. Since the 1960s, regional mining interests have caused significant damage to this site, destroying an estimated 5 to 25 percent of the petroglyphs in Murujuga. Today, Murujuga holds the unenviable status of being one of the most endangered archaeological sites in the world.José Antonio González Zarandona provides a full postcolonial analysis of Murujuga as well as a geographic and archaeological overview of the site, its ethnohistory, and its considerable significance to Indigenous groups, before examining the colonial mistreatment of Murujuga from the seventeenth century to the present. Drawing on a range of postcolonial perspectives, Zarandona reads the assaults on the rock art of Murujuga as instances of what he terms "landscape iconoclasm": the destruction of art and landscapes central to group identity in pursuit of ideological, political, and economic dominance. Viewed through the lens of landscape iconoclasm, the destruction of Murujuga can be understood as not only the result of economic pressures but also as a means of reinforcing—through neglect, abandonment, fragmentation, and even certain practices of heritage preservation—the colonial legacy in Western Australia. Murujuga provides a case study through which to examine, and begin to reject, archaeology's global entanglement with colonial intervention and the politics of heritage preservation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAboriginal AustralianszAustraliazBurrup Peninsula (W.A.)xAntiquities. 0aArtxMutilation, defacement, etczAustraliazBurrup Peninsula (W.A.). 0aArt, Aboriginal AustralianzAustraliazBurrup Peninsula (W.A.). 0aCultural propertyzAustraliazBurrup Peninsula (W.A.). 0aIconoclasm. 0aLandscape archaeologyzAustraliazBurrup Peninsula (W.A.). 0aPetroglyphszAustraliazBurrup Peninsula (W.A.). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aAnthropolog